	abstract = {The detection of aircraft skin defects is critical for aviation safety. Traditional manual inspections are inefficient and error-prone, while existing automated models struggle to identify small defects and operate efficiently in resource-constrained environments. We propose the Lightweight Guided and Shared Feature Fusion Network (LGSF-Net), integrating StarNet-based feature extraction, Adaptive Guided Feature Module (AGFM), and Shared Feature Detection (SFD) head. LGSF-Net achieves superior accuracy for small and medium-sized defects at just 3.0 megabyte (MB) and 139 frames per second (FPS), enabling real-time deployment on mobile platforms including drones. Our experiments show LGSF-Net significantly outperforms state-of-the-art models including You Only Look Once version 10 (YOLOv10), Real-Time Detection Transformer (RT-DETR), and You Only Look Once version 11 (YOLO11) while requiring 42 \% fewer parameters and 35 \% lower computational resources. LGSF-Net achieves 93.7 \% average precision (AP) on our Aircraft Skin Defect Dataset and demonstrates strong cross-domain generalization on Steel Surface Defect with 85.7 \% AP, Printed Circuit Board with 95.2 \% AP, and Vision Drone 2019 with 39.6 \% AP. This versatility makes LGSF-Net a transformative solution for aviation maintenance, with applications for automated drone-based inspection systems and potential to significantly reduce aircraft downtime, maintenance costs, and human error. Despite minor limitations under extreme conditions, LGSF-Net bridges the critical gap between detection accuracy and resource efficiency in safety-critical inspection workflows. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
