	abstract = {With the incorporation of data augmentations, the field of deep learning has advanced through significant improvement. Among these, CutMix stands out for improving the accuracy by combining patches of different images. However, it is still unclear why they provide a stable training process. This study focuses on evaluating the performance of normal augmentation as well as normal with CutMix augmentation by some specific training dynamic properties such as loss landscape, effective β -smoothness, and gradient predictiveness. We also aim to see if these properties can be upheld for generalizability. For this purpose, we train ResNet-50 and ConvMixer models on CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 datasets under both regular and CutMix augmentation conditions. Our analysis reveals that, in the case of effective β -smoothness and gradient predictiveness we can see a significant distinction in results between normal augmentation and advanced augmentation. The CutMix augmentation not only excels at better accuracy but also prevents variability and fluctuations in gradients. Additionally, through the loss landscape, we see that the ConvMixer shows lower training loss and ResNet exhibits stable training progression. Our findings contribute to a better understanding of augmentation benefits as well as model selection in neural network training and emphasize the importance of dynamic training properties in achieving optimal performance.},
