	abstract = {Deep learning-based methods have been widely used in product surface defect detection tasks. Recently, end-to-end mixed supervision networks based on end-to-end have performed well in industrial surface defect detection tasks, achieving better results than weakly supervised and fully supervised methods when weak labelling is allowed, but at significantly lower cost. However, the structure of such networks is complex and the learning process is slow. In this paper, we make lightweight improvements to the mixed supervision network, enabling the network to learn using a small number of positive samples, reducing the computational effort while maintaining network performance. We dynamically adjust the loss during learning and make the network more stable by adjusting the gradient flow during learning. The experiments on the defect detection dataset DAGM yielded good results. We also present a new dataset called MetalSDD(Metal Surface Defects Dataset), which contains more than 1000 images, mainly of rusted metal workpiece surfaces from real industrial environments. We show advanced results on two existing datasets. To validate the generality of the network, we also performed comparative experiments with the MetalSDD dataset against five currently popular anomaly detection networks, showing that our approach requires only a small amount of detailed annotation to produce comparable performance to the SOTA(state-of-the-art)model .},
