	abstract = {In response to issues such as poor real-time performance and complexity of network structure in the detection algorithm for surface defects on aluminum sheets, as well as difficulties in deploying on resource-constrained edge devices, a novel algorithm for aluminum sheet surface defect detection suitable for deployment on Field-Programmable Gate Arrays (FPGA) is proposed. Firstly, Shufflenetv2 is employed to replace the YOLOv5s backbone network, while the Focus layer in the model is removed to avoid repeated use of slice operations, reducing the parameter and computational complexity of the algorithm network model. Secondly, the improved Fast Spatial Pyramid Pooling (SPPF) module is embedded into the backbone network to enhance the algorithm’s detection accuracy. Finally, the Complete Intersection over Union (CIoU) loss function is replaced with Efficient Intersection over Union (EIoU). Results on the aluminum sheet defect dataset show that the detection speed reaches 90.3 frames per second on a PC, a 34\% improvement over the original version. Simulation on an FPGA development board demonstrates that the improved algorithm achieves a detection speed of 75.6 frames per second and an accuracy of 93.1\% mAP@0.5.},
